SIMPLE: grenadier
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grenadier
<hw>Gren`a*dier"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. grenadier.
See <er>Grenade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>
<def>Originaly, a soldier who carried and threw grenades; afterward, one
of a company attached to each regiment or battalion, taking post on the
right of the line, and wearing a peculiar uniform. In modern times, a
member of a special regiment or corps; <as>as, a <ex>grenadier</ex> of
the guard of Napoleon I.</as> one of the regiment of <ex>Grenadier</ex>
Guards of the British army, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The feats of grenadiers have been memorialized in song,
as in the following: (for the melody see
https://web.archive.org/web/20040202232801/http://www.acronet.net/~robokopp/english.html)
⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<TITLE>Some talk of Alexander, and some of Hercules / The British
Grenadiers</TITLE> <I>ca. 18th Century</I>

<H1>The British Grenadiers</H1> ⟦br⟧
Some talk of Alexander,⟦br⟧
And some of Hercules⟦br⟧
Of Hector and Lysander,⟦br⟧
And such great names as these.⟦br⟧
But of all the world's great heroes,⟦br⟧
There's none that can compare⟦br⟧
With a tow, row, row, row, row, row,⟦br⟧
To the British Grenadier.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
2. Those heroes of antiquity⟦br⟧
Ne'er saw a cannon ball⟦br⟧
Or knew the force of powder⟦br⟧
To slay their foes withall.⟦br⟧
But our brave boys do know it,⟦br⟧
And banish all their fears,⟦br⟧
Sing tow, row, row, row, row, row,⟦br⟧
For the British Grenadier.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
3. Whene'er we are commanded⟦br⟧
To storm the palisades⟦br⟧
Our leaders march with fusees,⟦br⟧
And we with hand grenades.⟦br⟧
We throw them from the glacis,⟦br⟧
About the enemies' ears.⟦br⟧
Sing tow, row, row, row, row, row,⟦br⟧
The British Grenadiers.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
4. And when the siege is over,⟦br⟧
We to the town repair⟦br⟧
The townsmen cry, "Hurra, boys,⟦br⟧
Here comes a Grenadier!"⟦br⟧
Here come the Grenadiers, my boys,⟦br⟧
Who know no doubts or fears!⟦br⟧
Then sing tow, row, row, row, row, row,⟦br⟧
The British Grenadiers.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
5. Then let us fill a bumper,⟦br⟧
And drink a health to those⟦br⟧
Who carry caps and pouches,⟦br⟧
And wear the louped clothes.⟦br⟧
May they and their commanders⟦br⟧
Live happy all their years⟦br⟧
With a tow, row, row, row, row, row,⟦br⟧
For the British Grenadiers.⟦br⟧
</note></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any marine fish of the genus
<gen>Macrurus</gen>, in which the body and tail taper to a point; they
mostly inhabit the deep sea; -- called also <altname>onion
fish</altname>, and <altname>rat-tail fish</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A bright-colored South African
grosbeak (<spn>Pyromelana orix</spn>), having the back red and the lower
parts black.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grenadillo</ent>⟦br⟧
